This program implements the "hunt and kill" algorithm for maze generation.

There is an implementation in pure C (huntkill.c), also there is an implementation
in x86-64 assembly language which is called from a C program (asm.asm/main.c).

The purpose of this repository is to demonstrate my skills with modern 64-bit
assembly language and interfacing assembly language routines with a C program.

To build: make sure nasm is installed on your machine:

Debian: sudo apt-get install nasm
Arch: sudo pacman -S nasm

make clean
make

Usage screen:

[ssviatko@catamaran huntkill]$ ./hk
usage: huntkill <height> <width> <cellheight> <cellwidth> <dumpfile>

Example run with 10x10 maze, displayed and sent to dumpfile:mazedump

[ssviatko@catamaran huntkill]$ ./hk 10 10 1 3 mazedump
---------------------------
|              |           |
   ---------      ------
|     |     |  |     |  |  |
---      ---   ---
|  |  |     |  |  |     |  |
                     ---
|  |  |  |     |     |  |  |
         ---------
|  |  |  |        |  |     |
      ---   ---   ------
|  |     |  |  |     |     |
   ---         ---      ---
|  |     |     |     |     |
      ---------
|  |     |     |  |  |  |  |
                     ---
|     |     |     |        |
---------------------------

Contents of mazedump file: each byte is a maze cell, bit 7 indicates if the cell
has been visited (used when generating the maze), bit 6 is the left wall, and
bit 5 is the top wall of the cell. The right wall and bottom wall are implied by
the adjacent cell, and consequently the right side column of cells are dedicated
to providing a solid left wall, and the bottom row of cells are dedicated to
providing a solid top wall for the bottom of the maze. Consequentally, a 10x10
array of cells will produce a 9x9 maze.

[ssviatko@catamaran huntkill]$ hexdump mazedump
0000000 c0e0 c0c0 e0c0 c0c0 20c0 c0a0 c0e0 a0a0
0000010 e0c0 20a0 a0e0 c0a0 e0a0 80a0 20a0 a0a0
0000020 a0a0 a080 e080 20a0 a0a0 e0a0 c0c0 a0a0
0000030 2080 a0a0 a0c0 a0e0 e0c0 2080 e0a0 a080
0000040 e080 a080 20c0 a0a0 e0c0 a0c0 a0a0 20a0
0000050 80a0 80a0 80a0 c0a0 2080 4040 4040 4040
0000060 4040 0040
0000064

Example 8x8 maze with cell height and with set to 3, 8 respectively
in order to print larger, easier to see cells:

[ssviatko@catamaran huntkill]$ ./hk 8 8 3 8 mazedump
